00:43.520 --> 00:49.760
legislation which the House passed and which the Senate is now considering to deny the trial

00:49.760 --> 00:55.520
of the right of a trial by jury. I have a pause there, of course. Of course, juries

00:55.520 --> 01:01.040
are sometimes make mistakes, and they are sometimes prejudiced. But I was reading a

01:01.040 --> 01:07.400
paragraph not so long ago from a book by Justice Woody Moe Dougies, which describes juries,

01:07.400 --> 01:13.040
their strength, as well as their shortcomings, about as well as anything I have seen. This

01:13.040 --> 01:19.040
paragraph states, as jury reflects the attitudes and the more rays of the community from which

01:19.040 --> 01:25.560
it is drawn. It lives only for the day and does justice according to its light. The group

01:25.560 --> 01:32.000
of 12 who are drawn to hear a case, make the decision, and melt away. It is not present

01:32.000 --> 01:38.280
the next day to be criticized. It is the one governmental agency that has no ambition. It

01:38.280 --> 01:43.960
is as human as the people who make it up. It is sometimes the victim of passion. But it

01:43.960 --> 01:50.960
also takes the sharp edges off a law and uses conscience to ameliorate a hardship. Since

01:50.960 --> 01:56.880
it is obvious and from the community, it gives the law an acceptance which critics of

01:56.880 --> 02:04.340
judges could not do. As the end of Justice Dougies' quotation, whether turned in jury by

02:04.340 --> 02:10.840
convicting the troublemaker and rabble rouse or John Casper and six of his court offenders,

02:10.840 --> 02:17.360
