02:23.080 --> 02:29.200
that the last sentence in Justice Dougies' remarks, it gives the law an acceptance which

02:29.200 --> 02:35.960
critics of judges could not do. It is important to remember in civil rights pieces which have

02:35.960 --> 02:41.800
a very important result on the attitudes of the community. As this broadcast is being

02:41.800 --> 02:47.680
prepared, we are debating the jury amendment. As you know, I filed an amendment which I discussed

02:47.680 --> 02:54.160
with you last week and which I think is workable. Senator O'Manney of Wyoming has filed a different

02:54.160 --> 02:59.360
type of amendment, but he has now abandoned his and adopted the same general approach that

02:59.360 --> 03:04.920
I do. I think it is safe to predict that the Senate will adopt an amendment similar

03:04.920 --> 03:09.040
to the one that we have been talking about, particularly since the end of the outcome of

03:09.040 --> 03:15.200
a sentence case. The amendment that we have been talking about retains the authority of

03:15.200 --> 03:19.880
the court to enforce its own orders without a jury, which I think is necessary for the

03:19.880 --> 03:25.760
dignity and for the authority of the court. But in any case where the person is to be criminally

03:25.760 --> 03:32.640
prosecuted, a jury is required. Earlier this week, the Senate voted to remove most of

03:32.640 --> 03:38.480
part three of the civil rights bill. I voted for that move. I believe that with the court's

03:38.480 --> 03:43.880
refreying of general problems, that it would be best not to attempt any new legislation

03:43.880 --> 03:49.320
in addition to the right to vote. In the final analysis, the bill that the Senate will

03:49.320 --> 03:55.560
pass, I believe, will be principally a right to vote bill. This, I think, is worthwhile.

03:55.560 --> 04:01.640
